<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   SRV Optimistic About Signing Documents With Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SRV Optimistic About Signing Documents With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1606142094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1326 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1606142094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, June 16 (XINHUA) -- Vietnamese Prime 
Minister Vo Van Kiet, who is in Moscow on a three-day official 
visit, remains optimistic about prospects of signing a bilateral 
treaty with Russia, though the sides failed to sign it during 
Thursday's [18 June] talks. 
  Commenting on his talks with Russian Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin, the Vietnamese premier told reporters: "Talks with 
the Russian side are going on productively. The new interstate 
treaty has been in general agreed upon and it is very important." 
  He said the document would be signed after certain 
improvements. The signing of the treaty, which was originally 
scheduled to take place at mid-day on Thursday, was put off till 
the evening. 
  A sources close to the Russian Government said the sides had 
failed to eliminate various disagreements during the talks 
between the two premiers. 
  Sources from the Vietnamese delegation explained that the 
disputed issues include prospecting and production of oil and 
natural gas by the joint "Vietsovpetro" venture, the problems of 
the Vietnamese community in Russia, as well as the Russian naval 
base in Cam Ranh. 
  To explain the delay of the signing of the documents, 
Chernomyrdin said that "matters of technical presentation" 
requiring specialists' attention cropped up during discussion. 
"Essentially, there have been no differences," he noted. 
  "We are convinced that Russia and Vietnam have every 
opportunity and potential to step up traditional cooperation in 
the commercial, economic, technological, scientific and other 
areas," he said. 
  However, the Vietnamese premier said the two sides differed 
on the following matters: the problem of paying off Vietnam's 
debt to Russia inherited from the former Soviet Union, terms of 
the operation of Cam Ranh base by the Russian Navy, and issues 
about the stay of Vietnamese citizens in Russia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

