<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   World's Major Companies Investing in China </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    World's Major Companies Investing in China </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706094894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0735 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706094894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By XINHUA correspondents Li Jianmin and Zhou Zongmin] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, June 17 (XINHUA) -- A growing number of 
the world's leading investors are flocking to China, a huge 
market of 1.2 billion people, as the country's economy continues 
booming. 
  Fifty-two giant transnational conglomerates, listed among 
the 
world's top 500 companies in the U.S. "FORTUNE" magazine, have 
pumped money into China since 1993, with a total contractual 
capital of four billion U.S. dollars, said officials from the 
State Administration of Industry and Commerce (SAIC), in a 
recent exclusive interview with XINHUA. 
  The arrival of leading international investors marked a 
significant shift in China's introduction of foreign investment 
which had been dominated by relatively small projects, the 
officials said. More fund and technology-intensive projects are 
coming in, they added. 
  "China's fast-growing economy and improved investment 
environment are major factors behind the transnational 
companies' favoring China," said Martin Claus, chief 
representative of the German KHD Company's Beijing office. KHD, 
one of the most prestigious engineering firms in the world, is 
now close to signing a 400- million-U.S. dollar contract with 
China. 
  China's economy has been growing at double-digit pace over 
the past several years and is expected to grow 12 percent in the 
first half of this year and 10 percent for the whole year. 
  Latest statistics indicate that transnational companies 
account for about half of the total foreign investment in China 
since 1993. 
  According to the SAIC officials, over 3,700 foreign firms 
have established representative offices or branches in China 
since the beginning of last year, including some 260 powerful 
companies. Among them are big names like Du Pont, General 
Electric, Siemens, IBM, Philips, Mitsubishi and National. While 
bringing investments to China, the transnationals have come 
along with more projects of technical cooperation. 
  Apart from Western firms, rising giants from 
newly-industrialized countries and regions, such as Singapore 
and the Republic of Korea, are also elbowing for a share in the 
Chinese market. 
  A survey conducted recently by an international organization 
shows that 98 percent of U.S. firms interviewed have listed 
China as the best place for investment. 
  Attracting big transnational firms has been China's main 
target in the 1990s. Foreign investments in chunks up to 10 
million dollars are most welcome, particularly in key economic 
fields such as infrastructure and basic industries. 
  More big international firms are putting money in these 
sectors as well as the service industries, said an official of 
the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation. 
  China has announced that its imports will be as high as 
1,000 
billion dollars in the remaining years before the end of the 
century. And foreign investors now face a good prospect. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

