<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-117 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports on Carter's DPRK Trip </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Reports on Carter's DPRK Trip </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706101094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0958 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706101094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 17 (XINHUA) -- South Korea has decided 
to concentrate on a peaceful settlement of the nuclear problem 
of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) through 
dialogue such as a high-level meeting between Washington and 
Pyongyang. 
  The decision was made at a Unification and Security Policy 
Coordination Committee Meeting presided over by Deputy Prime 
Minister and National Unification Board (NUB) Minister Yi 
Hong-ku here Friday [17 June]. 
  Former President of the United States Jimmy Carter, who is 
currently on a visit in Pyongyang, held first round of talks 
with the DPRK's President Kim Il-song yesterday on ways to find 
a solution to the nuclear issue. 
  Kim was quoted as telling Carter that his country has 
changed 
its mind and will let two inspectors of the International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA) remain in the DPRK. 
  Meanwhile, Carter reportedly said that Washington-Pyongyang 
high- level talks may resume if the DPRK freezes its nuclear 
program. 
  The U.S. and the DPRK held two rounds of high-level talks on 
the nuclear issue in June and July last year. The third round 
of talks, which had been scheduled for March 21 this year, was 
cancelled due to differences between the two sides. 
  The South Korean Government will announce its position on 
Pyongyang's new sign of reconciliation after President Kim 
Yong-sam meets with Carter again over the weekend, officials 
here said. 
  Carter, who went to Pyongyang through the heavily-fortified 
border village of Panmunjom after a three-day visit to South 
Korea, will return to Seoul via Panmunjom Saturday to brief 
President Kim Yong-sam on the results of his talks with DPRK 
leaders before heading back to Washington. 
  The former U.S. President said earlier that his trip would 
be 
a private one aiming "to discuss some of the important issues of 
the day with leaders of the area." 
  The United States yesterday submitted a draft resolution at 
the United Nations Security Council calling for sanctions 
against the DPRK, which on Monday withdrew from IAEA, the United 
Nations nuclear watchdog, and declared not to accept any more 
inspections of its nuclear program. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

