<F P=100> Southeast Asia &amp; Pacific </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cambodia's Round-Table Peace Talks Fail </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cambodia's Round-Table Peace Talks Fail </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1606141194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1318 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1606141194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Phnom Penh, June 16 (XINHUA) -- The round-table 
meeting on peace and national reconciliation in Cambodia ended 
Thursday [16 June] with the royal government and the Democratic 
Kampuchea Party (DKP) failing to reach agreement on a cease-fire 
and a minimum political principle. 
  After the meeting, a spokesman for the royal government 
admitted that nothing came out of the meeting but added that it 
was "not a failure." 
  The spokesman said that during the meeting, the royal 
government side offered a deadline of noon on June 30 for a 
cease-fire to be imposed, while the DKP wished to discuss the 
details of establishing a monitoring committee. 
  The DKP criticized the government side for refusing to 
discuss in depth the problem of monitoring a cease-fire and 
refusing to discuss the minimum political principle on peace and 
national reconciliation. 
  The round table meeting opened on Wednesday and although 
neither side has decided whether to hold another, the 
possibility of further talks depends on King Norodom Sihanouk. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

