<H3> <TI>   Philippine Exports to China Expected To Increase </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Philippine Exports to China Expected To Increase </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1606120794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1045 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1606120794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Manila, June 16 (XINHUA) -- The Philippines' exports 
to China is projected to increase by 70 percent this year 
following the signing of a protocol on the importation and 
exportation of commodities between the two countries, an 
industry leader said today. 
  Philippine Chamber of Commerce and Industry President Herman 
Montenegro, who recently visited China together with a 
Philippine trade mission, said there is vast opportunities for 
Philippine products in China. 
  Montenegro said Philippine construction materials like 
saniware products are hot and fast selling items in China as the 
country is currently experiencing a wave of construction 
activity. 
  In Beijing alone, he said, some 10 million square meters is 
being constructed annually. 
  The bilateral trade between the Philippines and China 
amounted to 480 million U.S. dollars and is expected to increase 
by 35 percent this year, according to the Department of Trade 
and Industry. 
  The trade mission, Montenegro said, was able to establish a 
trade desk in Guangdong Province which would help establish 
contact between Chinese and Filipino businessmen. 
  Another mission is being planned for October this year with 
the objective of organizing focus groups in Beijing, Shanghai, 
Xiamen and Guandong, Montenegro said. 

</TEXT>

