<F P=100> Southeast Asia &amp; Pacific </F>
<H3> <TI>   Australia Appoints Senior Representative to Shanghai </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Australia Appoints Senior Representative to Shanghai </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706073494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0711 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706073494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Canberra, June 17 (XINHUA) -- The Australian Trade 
Commission (Austrade), the government trade arms, has appointed 
Martin Walsh senior trade commissioner to Shanghai, China's 
largest industrial and financial center. 
  Walsh said today that as Shanghai is increasingly taking on 
the role of China's financial and industrial hub, "Austrade is 
now expanding its services in Shanghai." 
  This is in line with the government initiative to help 
Australian business get better access to the tremendous 
development now going on in the east China region, he said in a 
statement. 
  Walsh, who will take up his position on July 15, has been 
manager of Austrade's east Asia regional support office in 
Sydney since 1993. 
  Speaking fluent mandarin Chinese and with an extensive 
background in Chinese business culture, Walsh was posted as 
Austrade trade commissioner in south China from 1985 to 1988 and 
as trade development director at the Australian Commerce and 
Industry Office in Taipei from 1989 to 1992. 
  He said that "Shanghai itself is growing rapidly" and he 
would focus on its Pudong Economic Development Zone. 
  "We are focusing strongly on the new Pudong finance and 
industrial development area on the opposite bank of the Huangpu 
River to the Bund," he added. 
  He said that "this will be a massive commercial center." 
  Australia has shifted its trade focus to Asia in recent 
years 
in a hope of taking advantage of booming economies in the Asian 
region to give an impetus to the country's economy. 
  Trade and economic ties between China and Australia have 
increased in the past years as the thriving economic growth in 
China, especially in east China, has lured more Australian 
business. 
  Australia's investment in China has reached to 1.25 billion 
U.S. dollars in terms of contracted value by the end of last 
year, making it the 9th largest foreign investor in China. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

