<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economy, Inflation Continue Double-Digit Growth in May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Economy, Inflation Continue Double-Digit Growth in May </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1706103794 Beijing CHINA DAILY in English 17 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> HK1706103794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Wu Yunhe: "Industrial Growth Hits 17 Percent While </F>
Inflation Lingers"] 
  [Text] China's economy continued its double-digit growth 
last month despite lingering inflation. 
  Industrial output hit 17.3 per cent in May the State 
Statistics Bureau announced yesterday. 
  The growth in production is due to the easing of credit 
controls by the government, which in turn has led to a rise in 
capital investment, said the bureau's economists. 
  And, Xinhua News Agency quoted an official from the State 
Economic and Trade Commission as saying that the GDP is expected 
to grow by about 12 per cent in the first half of this year, 
making it easier for the country to achieve the 9-10 GDP per 
cent growth in 1994. [sentence as published] 
  The fixed assets invested by work units hit 67.6 billion 
yuan 
($7.8 billion) in May, up nearly 28 per cent from the same month 
last year, the statistics bureau reported. 
  During the first five months of this year, State units 
invested 204.4 billion yuan ($23.5 billion) in the country's 
fixed assets sector, representing a rise of 34.2 percent over 
the same period a year ago the bureau said. 
  Of this, money used for construction accounted for 114.1 
billion yuan ($13.1 billion), up 35.1 percent over the same 
period last year. 
  Inflation also continued its double-digit growth this year, 
the bureau said. 
  In May, the cost of living index in the country was 21.3 per 
cent, higher than the same time of last year. But this was 0.4 
per cent lower than the growth of 21.7 per cent reported a month 
earlier. 
  The bureau's economists said living costs have been 
persistently high in the country's big cities, partly because of 
random price hikes of food and catering services. 
  The inflation in the country's 35 large and medium cities 
saw 
a growth of 23.2 per cent in April. And in May, the prices 
continued to grow at the same level. 
  Government departments should maintain strict control over 
the prices in a bid to meet this year's inflation target of 10 
per cent nationwide and 15 percent in major cities, as 
designated by the central government, said the economists. 
  They noted that efforts to increase bank savings and issuing 
treasury bonds are helping to curb inflation. 
  Banks and credit companies saw their individual and 
institutional savings increase by 113.4 billion yuan ($13 
billion) last month. The figure was 79.4 billion yuan ($9.1 
billion) higher than the same period last year, the bureau said. 
  And by the end of May, the State had sold more than 68.1 
billion yuan ($7.8billion) worth of treasury bonds. 
  It included the sale of two-year bonds valued at 24.8 
billion 
yuan ($2.8 billion), more than meeting the planned target, the 
bureau said. 
  A growth of bank savings and the brisk sale of State 
treasury 
bonds lead to a 33.7 percent growth in State revenue in May. 
  The success of financial reforms also helped to stimulate 
industrial growth in the already buoyant domestic market. 
  In May, the country's retail sales totalled 121.4 billion 
yuan ($14 billion), up 6.1 percent over the same period of last 
year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-26058 </DOCNO>
