<F P=100> Southwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tibet Cultivates Meteorological Professionals </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tibet Cultivates Meteorological Professionals </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1506142894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1410 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1506142894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lhasa, June 15 (XINHUA) -- The Tibet Meteorological 
Bureau stresses cultivation of Tibetan professionals for the 
weather forecast sector. 
  Since 1981, the bureau has selected 520 Tibetans from the 
region and sent them to study in specialized schools and 
universities in inland provinces. 
  Now the proportion of Tibetan weather men to the total has 
increased from 18.6 percent to 70.3 percent. 
  Of all technological personnel in the Tibet meteorological 
sector, the Tibetan technicians account for more than 50 percent. 
  Purpu Cering is the first Tibetan to graduate from Nanjing 
Meteorology Institute, China's most prestigious in the field, 
with a master's degree. Last year, he went to the United States 
to participate in a modern meteorology program with the 
recommendation of the National Meteorological Bureau. 
  The 25-year-old engineer completed several research projects 
and returned with high praise from Chinese and foreign experts. 
  This year, the Tibet Meteorological Bureau selected six 
young 
Tibetans to enter Nanjing Meteorology Institute's master's 
program. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

