<F P=100> Northwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gansu Benfits From Water, Soil Control Project </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gansu Benfits From Water, Soil Control Project </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706035594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0317 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706035594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lanzhou, June 17 (XINHUA) -- People of northwest 
China's Gansu Province who have suffered a lot from water loss 
and soil erosion are now benefiting from a government water and 
soil control project. 
  In the southern part of Gansu Province, which covers an area 
of 3,345 square kilometers, the poverty-stricken areas have 
dropped from 66 percent to 18 percent as a result of a five-year 
effort in water and soil control drive. 
  For a long time in the past, the southern part of Gansu, 
including the Qingba Mountain areas and the upper reaches of the 
Chang Jiang River, was one of the four main areas in China 
suffering from mud-rock flow. It now has over 800 crevasses 
caused by mud- rock flows and over 200 remains of landslides. 
  In 1988, the Chinese State Council designated seven counties 
in southern Gansu as key project areas for water and soil 
control. Since then, more than 10 million yuan (about 1.2 
million U.S. Dollars) has been invested in the project each year. 
  As part of the project, land has been terraced, trees 
planted 
and grass sown in a 3,345 square kilometer area. Local people 
describe the project as "life engineering". 
  The project has brought 57 percent of water loss and soil 
erosion under control. 
  The forest coverage in the area has increased by 4 percent. 
  With the improving of farming conditions, the grain output 
in 
the area has increased. Last year, the total grain output was 
716 million kilograms, a record for the area. 
  Production centers for apples, oranges and Chinese prickly 
ash have emerged along rivers and in mountain areas in the south 
of Gansu Province. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

