<F P=100> PRC MEDIA ON TAIWAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wang Daohan Sends Letter to Taiwan's Gu Zhenfu </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Wang Daohan Sends Letter to Taiwan's Gu Zhenfu </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706092494 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0537 
GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1706092494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 17 (XINHUA) -- Wang Daohan, chairman 
of the Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Strait 
[ARATS], today sent a letter to Gu Zhenfu [Ku Chen-fu], 
president of the Straits Exchange Foundation [SEF], to invite 
him once again to hold a high-level meeting between the two 
organizations at a selected place. 
  The letter reads: One year ago, the Wang-Gu talks made an 
historically significant step in the development of cross-strait 
relations. I am pleased to see that various contacts and 
exchanges between the two sides of the Taiwan Strait have been 
conducted vigorously since then. Some progress has been made in 
implementing the agreement during the five negotiations between 
the colleagues of ARATS and the SEF. Particularly during the 
meeting between Mr. Tang Shubei and Jiao Renhe [Chaio Jen-he] 
early this year, a high degree of consensus was reached in terms 
of routine discussions between ARATS and the SEF. The meeting 
made a plan for this year's ARATS-SEF negotiations and other 
issues relating to the negotiations and achieved another interim 
result in promoting ARATS-SEF relations and cooperation since 
the Wang-Gu talks. It is my belief that various results which 
have been achieved since the Wang-Gu talks should be highly 
valued. 
  The letter continues: Since the unfortunate "Qiandao Lake 
Incident" occurred, the development of cross-strait relations 
have been adversely affected. I am very impressed by your 
active and reasonable attitude towards maintaining the overall 
development of cross-strait relations. Amid heavy mists and 
obstacles, the two organizations should work even harder to push 
forward ARATS-SEF negotiations and exchanges. Maintaining and 
promoting the development of cross-strait relations with a 
100-times greater enthusiasm has a bearing on consolidating and 
developing the original intention and achievements of the 
Wang-Gu talks. There is no reason for relaxation. It is highly 
necessary to hold a high-level meeting for communications and 
contacts. 
  The letter says: I sent you a letter early this year, 
inviting you to visit Beijing during the turn of spring and 
summer. I learned that you would be very glad to come to the 
Mainland to meet me. Recently, you wrote an article expressing 
the hopes to further strengthen high-ranking contacts between 
the two organizations. I deem it highly necessary to hold such 
a meeting. Strengthening high-ranking contacts between the two 
organizations is beneficial to further improving understanding, 
eliminating misunderstanding, overcoming discrepancies, and 
promoting cooperation in a bid to create an atmosphere of 
frequent exchanges and relaxation for the meeting. I would like 
to renew my suggestion to hold a meeting for reviewing ARATS-SEF 
cooperation, discussing ways to strengthen our ties and expand 
our cooperation, and conducting communications on policy-related 
issues and other issues. If it is inconvenient for you [to come 
to Beijing], such a meeting can be held in Taipei or another 
place agreed upon. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-26080 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi117_u_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-117 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> PRC MEDIA ON TAIWAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Calls For Urgent Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Calls For Urgent Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706082994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0813 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706082994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 17 (XINHUA) -- A senior leader from a 
mainland non-governmental organization sent a letter Thursday 
[17 June] to his counterpart in Taiwan, expressing hopes to meet 
again soon with the head of the Taiwan-based organization. 
  Wang Daohan, president of the Association for Relations 
Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS), based on the mainland, wrote 
to Ku Chen-fu, chairman of the board and secretary general of 
the Taiwan-based Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF), saying that 
the latest developments in relations across the straits called 
for an urgent meeting between the two organizations. 
  Wang said that the contacts between them would help further 
increase understanding, remove misunderstandings, overcome 
differences and promote cooperation. 
  The proposed talks, he said, could explore ways to forge 
closer contacts and expand cooperation. Wang proposed that they 
should meet in Taipei, or elsewhere if Ku prefers. Wang 
recalled that in a letter earlier this year he had invited Ku to 
Beijing for talks in late spring or early summer, and that 
sources then said that Ku would be happy to meet Wang on the 
mainland. Ku also wrote recently in an article expressing his 
wish to strengthen contacts. 
  In his letter, Wang said that the Wang-Ku talks a year ago 
had ushered in an important historical step in the development 
of relations across the straits, adding that exchanges in 
various sectors have been developing vigorously, marking the 
progress made in the five talks to settle the remaining issues 
in the agreements reached between Wang and Ku during their talks 
in Singapore. 
  Wang especially noted that the talks between Tang Shubei and 
Chiao Jen-ho early this year had reached a high degree of common 
understanding concerning talks on routine issues, and had 
drafted an outline for this year's talks between the two 
organisations. 
  He said the relations across the straits had been affected 
by 
the Qiandao Lake tragedy which claimed the lives of 24 Taiwan 
tourists. But Wang spoke highly of Ku's positive and rational 
stand to safeguard the relations across the straits. 
  "Amidst the rumors and misunderstandings, we should 
intensify 
our efforts to push ahead with the talks and exchanges between 
the two sides," Wang wrote. 
  This would be in line with the original intention and would 
consolidate the achievements already made, and therefore calls 
for talks between high-ranking leaders of the ARATS and SEF as 
soon as possible, Wang added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

