Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Sees No `Thaw' in Sino-British Relations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Sees No `Thaw' in Sino-British Relations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1706050294 Hong Kong HONGKONG STANDARD in English 17 Jun 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> HK1706050294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong HONGKONG STANDARD </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Jim Cheung, and M.Y. Sung in Beijing] </F>
  [Text] A senior government official has said that he saw 
no evidence of a thaw in Sino-British relations when he met 
senior officials in charge of Hong Kong affairs in Beijing this 
week, despite recent declarations by China that its political 
row with Britain would not thwart cooperation. Secretary for 
Trade and Industry Brian Chau was in Beijing on official 
business, when Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen and director 
of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office Lu Ping, declared that 
two of the biggest obstacles to Sino-British cooperation could 
quickly be resolved. 
  During his trip, Mr Chau met the affair's office Deputy 
Director Chen Ziying and department head Wang Fengchao. Mr Chau 
said while his contact with both officials was brief and 
friendly, their position had not changed since the political row 
first began. "Their attitude towards me was the same when I last 
saw them two years ago," he said. 
  In Beijing, the Foreign Ministry continued to speak of 
conciliation, but stressed that continuing cooperation depended 
on Britain's attitude. "The Chinese side hopes that 
difficulties over the question of Hong Kong will not affect ties 
between the two countries in other areas," Foreign Ministry 
spokesman Shen Guofang said. "The Chinese side is willing to 
have further cooperation with the British side. But whether it 
can be done depends on what approach and action the British side 
takes." 
  The chairman of the Federation of Trade Unions Cheng 
Yiu-tong, who led a delegation to Beijing this week, said he was 
convinced that China was determined to shelve the long-running 
political row and resume cooperation with Britain. "Mr Qian 
emphasised that the deadlock over 1994-95 electoral reform was 
over," Mr Cheng said. "He said that China would strengthen 
economic cooperation with Britain to ensure a smooth transition 
in the remaining years." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

