<HT>    "drchi117_b_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-117 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton Remarks Further </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clinton Remarks Further </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706001194 Beijing XINHUA in English 2352 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706001194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, June 16 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President Bill 
Clinton said here today that the U.S. would be willing to reopen 
negotiations with the Democratic People's Republic of Korea 
(DPRK) if the DPRK cooperates with the International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA). 
  Clinton said at a White House press conference today that 
there are reports that the DPRK may have offered new steps to 
resolve its nuclear dispute with the U.S. and the IAEA. 
  In discussions with U.S. former President Jimmy Carter who 
is 
in Pyongyang for a private visit, DPRK leaders said that IAEA's 
inspectors and monitoring equipment would be left in place, 
according to Clinton. 
  The DPRK also "desires to replace its present nuclear 
program 
with a new light water reactor technology that is more resistant 
to nuclear proliferation," Clinton said. 
  Clinton said he is interested in hearing more about the 
DPRK's offer and described the latest development as a promising 
one. 
  "If today's development mean that North Korea is genuinely 
and verifiably prepared to freeze its nuclear program while 
talks go on," Clinton said, "then we would be willing to resume 
high-level talks." 
  But in the meantime, the United States will continue to 
pursue its consultations on sanction against the DPRK at the 
United Nations, Clinton added. 
  "We are hopeful that this development today will be 
positive, 
and we are awaiting further evidence," Clinton said. 
  Before Clinton made the remarks, the White House issued a 
statement, saying that "the United States welcomes indications 
given to President Carter [as received] that North Korea desires 
to find a constructive solution to the very serious issues 
between North Korea and the international community." 
  "After confirming this meaning of the message from North 
Korea in diplomatic channels, we would be prepared to go to a 
third round of talks," Assistant Secretary of State Robert 
Gallucci said in the statement. 
  "The point today, I think, for you is that there may be in 
this message a basis for returning to talks with the North 
Koreans," Gallucci said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

