<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ren Jianxin: Courts Can `Learn' From Other Nations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ren Jianxin: Courts Can `Learn' From Other Nations </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Speaks at World Law Conference </H4>

<F P=102> OW1706081594 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0746 
GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1706081594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Haikou, 15 Jun (XINHUA) -- China's courts have 
brought their judicial role into full play and scored notable 
achievements in conducting foreign affairs and promoting 
judicial exchanges with foreign countries. 
  According to information released by the national conference 
on the foreign affairs of courts now being held in Haikou, from 
1983 to 1993, the supreme court sent a total of 125 delegations 
(groups) of 429 people abroad for visits; received 113 foreign 
delegations of 554 members; established ties with courts in 
nearly 100 countries and regions; and conducted exchanges with 
the International Court and other international organizations. 
Beijing's successful hosting of the 14th World Law Congress in 
1990 gave a strong impetus to promoting China's judicial 
exchanges with foreign countries and won the international 
community's understanding and support. 
  In a written speech to the conference, Ren Jianxin, member 
of 
the CPC Central Committee Secretariat and president of the 
Supreme People's Court, emphasized: Courts' foreign affairs are 
an important component of the government's overall diplomacy. 
People's courts should learn from the useful experiences of 
other countries' courts in continuing to improve and perfect a 
socialist judicial system with Chinese characteristics so as to 
better fulfill the judicial tasks laid on them by the 
constitution and to better serve the socialist modernization 
drive. Courts' foreign affairs work should play a more active 
role and make greater contributions in this area. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

