Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Northwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Xinjiang Residents Make Progress Against Poverty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Xinjiang Residents Make Progress Against Poverty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1506142794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1420 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1506142794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Urumqi, June 15 (XINHUA) -- More than 300,000 
families of farmers and herdsmen in northwest China's Xinjiang 
Uygur Autonomous Region have eliminated poverty in the past few 
years thanks to scientific progress. 
  According to statistics from the region, it had 353,700 poor 
families comprising more than 1.6 million people by the end of 
1985. 
  To help these people shake off poverty, the region put more 
efforts into teaching them agricultural technologies and 
techniques rather than simply giving them money as before. 
  The regional commission of science and technology, the 
regional women's federation and the agricultural department of 
the region have composed a complete program to aid the poor by 
setting up evening schools and training classes and offering 
correspondence courses and hands-on teaching. 
  By now, about 85 percent of the poor farmers and herdsmen 
have mastered one or two practical techniques. 
  The region has also sent thousands of scientists and 
technicians to the grassroots level to help the poor people. 
  As the region suffers from a lack of rain, the regional 
government began to build 90 irrigation works in 1986. Now it 
has poured 300 million yuan into these projects, among which 46 
have been completed. 
  These projects have increased the reservoir water reserve of 
the region by 90 million cubic meters and irrigated more than 
80,000 hectares of farmlands and grasslands. 

</TEXT>

