<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-117 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Says Beijing Trying To Alienate Taipei Firms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Says Beijing Trying To Alienate Taipei Firms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1606134194 Taipei CNA in English 1314 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1606134194 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Sofia Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, June 16 (CNA) -- The Beijing-based 
Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Strait (ARATS) is 
stepping up contacts with Taiwan investors in Mainland China in 
an attempt to have them cut their relations with Taiwan, a 
high-ranking mainland affairs official said Thursday [16 June]. 
  Huang Kun-hui, chairman of the Mainland Affairs Council 
(MAC), said during a cabinet meeting that ARATS Chairman Wang 
Daohan and Standing Vice Chairman Tang Shubei have visited many 
southeastern mainland cities where a number of Taiwan-owned 
companies are located, including Ningbo, Hangzhou, Nanjing, 
Yangzhou, Wuxi and Suzhou, since mid-May. 
  Wang and Tang have met intensively with senior executives of 
Taiwan-invested firms during their tours of those cities, Huang 
said. They have also held face-to-face talks with Taiwan youths 
studying there. 
  [Words indistinct] might be aiming to win back the hearts of 
Taiwan businessmen whose confidence in mainland authorities has 
been adversely affected by the Qiandao Lake travel disaster in 
which 24 tourists were killed, Huang noted. 
  "The two might also be implementing resolutions reached 
during a Beijing meeting in April on a new strategy toward 
Taiwan to intensify courting Taiwan investors," Huang said. 
  Huang also said that ARATS has adopted a sugar-coated 
conciliatory approach to win the trust of Taiwan businessmen. 
"Wang seems to be talking Taiwan investors into believing that 
ARATS can speak for them and protect their interests and rights 
on the mainland," he explained. 
  On the other hand, he said ARATS has deliberately ignored 
the 
call from the Taipei-based Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF) for 
cooperation in assisting mainland China-based Taiwan companies 
to resolve their problems. 
  "By doing so, ARATS aims to alienate Taiwan companies from 
the SEF," Huang said, adding that ARATS hopes those firms will 
in the long run exclusively turn to it for assistance and 
gradually cut their ties with their homeland. 
  The SEF and ARATS are semi-official bodies set up by their 
respective governments to handle cross-strait exchanges in the 
absence of official contacts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

