Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nuclear Crisis in DPRK `Over' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nuclear Crisis in DPRK `Over' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1906225494 Beijing XINHUA in English 2222 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1906225494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Carter: Nuclear Crisis in DPRK Is Over"] </F>
  [Text] Washington, June 19 (XINHUA) -- Former president of 
the United States Jimmy Carter said here today he thought that 
the crisis with the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) 
is over. 
  Carter told reporters after meeting with U.S. Administration 
officials at the White House that as far as he was concerned, 
"there are no unanswered questions" following his talks with 
DPRK leaders on how to resolve the unclear crisis. 
  Carter, who returned from the DPRK on Saturday [18 June], 
had 
about two-hour meetings at the White House with National 
Security Adviser Tony Lake, Assistant Secretary of State Robert 
Gallucci, Assistant Secretary of State for Asia Winston Lord and 
other officials. 
  Before speaking to reporters, Carter talked by telephone for 
about half an hour with U.S. President Bill Clinton, who is 
spending the weekend at Camp David. 
  "I personally believe that the crisis is over," Carter said, 
"and I personally believe that Kim Il-song wants to be sure that 
the crisis is over." 
  "I personally don't see any need to proceed with the 
sanctions unless there is some violation of the agreement I have 
received," Carter stressed. 
  Carter said he expected the third round of talks between the 
U.S. and the DPRK could be arranged within the next few weeks 
and that confirmation of the latest agreements through 
diplomatic channels could get under way as soon as this week. 
  "It may well be that President Carter has brought back 
something upon which we can build and defuse the situation," 
Gallucci told reporters after Carter left the White House. 
  He said the Clinton administration would move as quickly as 
possible to meet with DPRK officials and discuss the proposals 
brought back by Carter. 
  However, Lake said that the United States's efforts to 
obtain 
sanctions against the DPRK would only be suspended after formal 
talks between the two countries begin. 
  "In the meantime," Lake said, "we are continuing to consult 
on the sanctions" at the United Nations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

