<H3> <TI>   Americans `Support' Resumption of Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Americans `Support' Resumption of Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1906054994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0530 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1906054994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, June 18 (XINHUA) -- Most Americans 
support the U.S. Administration to resume talks with the 
Democratic Peoples' Republic of Korea (DPRK), a NEWSWEEK 
magazine poll said today. 
  The poll showed that nearly 68 percent of 499 Americans 
interviewed by telephone believed the United States should 
resume talks with the DPRK. 
  Twenty-five percent were against resuming talks before 
inspections on the DPRK's nuclear facilities, and seven percent 
said they didn't know, the poll said. 
  U.S. President Bill Clinton said Thursday [19 Jun] that the 
U.S. would be willing to resume high-level talks with the DPRK 
if the DPRK is ready to freeze its nuclear program while talks 
go on. 

</TEXT>

