<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Reaffirms Readiness To Resume Talks With DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Reaffirms Readiness To Resume Talks With DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1906064794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0558 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1906064794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, June 18 (XINHUA) -- The United States 
reiterated today that it will resume talks with the Democratic 
Peoples' Republic of Korea (DPRK) if the DPRK is ready to freeze 
its nuclear program. 
  The U.S. Administration will discuss the DPRK's position 
with 
U.S. former President Jimmy Carter who just ended his private 
visit to the DPRK today, White House Press Secretary Dee Dee 
Myers said in a statement. 
  It was reported that the DPRK told Carter it will agree to 
allow the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) inspectors 
to stay in the DPRK and to replace its present nuclear program 
with a new light water reactor technology. 
  President Bill Clinton said Thursday [16 Jun] if this 
development means that the DPRK "is genuinely and verifiably 
prepared to freeze its nuclear program while talks go on", then 
the U.S. will be willing to resume high-level talks with the 
DPRK. 
  Myers said that preliminary reports on Carter's visit 
"present the possibility that the North Koreans may be prepared 
to make commitments and take actions" that would pave the way 
for a new round of talks. 
  The U.S. would also seek confirmation through "diplomatic 
channels" on the DPRK's position, she added. 
  "If this meaning of the message is clearly confirmed through 
those channels, and we hope it will be, we would be prepared to 
enter a third round of talks to resolve the outstanding issues 
between North Korea and the international community," Myers said. 
  But she also said that "we are continuing to consult on a 
sanctions resolution at the U.N. Security Council." 

</TEXT>

