<H3> <TI>   Beijing Calls For Regular International AIDS Conferences </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Beijing Calls For Regular International AIDS Conferences </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1806040694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0330 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1806040694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, June 17 (XINHUA) -- China today called for 
regular high-level meetings supported by the developed nations 
to coordinate efforts against AIDS in the developing world and 
other hard-hit regions. 
  The call was made by Chinese Health Minister Chen Minzhang 
at 
a ministerial level international conference in Paris, which is 
being held ahead of a Paris summit proposed by France for 
December 1 on the fight against the killer disease. 
  China supports international and trans-regional cooperation 
in the fight against AIDS, said Chen, stressing that more 
attention and efforts should be given to anti-AIDS plans in 
developing countries. 
  It urges neighboring states to coordinate their efforts to 
fight AIDS by setting up information networks and developing 
regional cooperation projects, he added. 
  Chen also briefed the conference on the Chinese Government's 
anti-AIDS work and pledged to make contribution to the global 
strategy against AIDS. 
  The two-day conference, which started today, is being 
attended by ministers from 50 nations and representatives of 
some world health agencies. 

</TEXT>

