<H3> <TI>   President Clinton Seeks Authority on Trade Accords </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Clinton Seeks Authority on Trade Accords </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706223094 Beijing XINHUA in English 2209 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706223094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, June 17 (XINHUA) -- The Clinton 
administration asked Congress here today for special authority 
to negotiate free trade agreements with Latin American countries. 
  Some of these countries have expressed the hope that they be 
included in an expanded North American Free Trade Agreement 
(NAFTA) which links the U.S., Canada and Mexico. 
  With fast-track authority, sought by the administration when 
negotiating NAFTA and the General Agreement of Tariffs and 
Trade, the trade agreement negotiated by the administration 
allows no congressional amendment. 
  Sources said bilateral negotiations between the U.S. and 
Chile on the latter's joining of NAFTA will begin later this 
year. Chile reportedly hoped the agreement can be concluded by 
early 1995. 

</TEXT>

