<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Premier Says Japan Possesses Nuclear Capability </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Premier Says Japan Possesses Nuclear Capability </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706141694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1355 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706141694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 17 (XINHUA) -- Japanese Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata said today that Japan has the capability to produce 
nuclear weapons and it has not done so because of its 
international treaty obligations, the Tokyo news service 
reported. 
  "It's certainly the case that Japan has the capability to 
possess nuclear weapons but has not made them," KYODO quoted 
Hata as telling Japanese reporters inside the Diet (parliament) 
building. 
  He said Japan has abstained from doing so in line with its 
obligations as a non-nuclear state under the nuclear 
Nonproliferation Treaty (NPT), KYODO said. 
  Hata made the comment in connection with an alleged remark 
made in a House of Councillors Budget Committee meeting earlier 
in the day. 
  The prime minister was quoted by parliamentarians as having 
said he "agrees absolutely" with an interpellator's views that 
Japan should confirm to other nations that it can indeed produce 
nuclear weapons, though it is refraining from doing so for 
political reasons. 
  The interpellator, opposition Liberal Democratic Party 
member 
Hiroshi Oki, cited the NPT and Japan's three non-nuclear 
principles -- not possessing, manufacturing or introducing 
nuclear weapons on its territory. 
  KYODO said Hata denied to the press at first that he made 
the 
alleged remark, though Oki insisted that the prime minister 
"roundly affirmed" Japan's potential for producing nuclear 
weapons. 
  It is believed to be the first time for the Japanese 
Government to publicly acknowledge such potential in the Diet or 
public, the news service said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

