<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports ROK Acceptance of Summit Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Reports ROK Acceptance of Summit Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1806100694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0952 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1806100694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 18 (XINHUA) -- South Korean President 
Kim Yong-sam accepted today a proposal made by Kim Il-song, 
president of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), 
to hold an inter-Korean summit aimed at tackling the nuclear 
issue on the Korean peninsula. 
  Former U.S. President Jimmy Carter, who arrived here 
Saturday 
[18 June] morning following his four-day private visit to the 
DPRK, conveyed DPRK President Kim Il-song's proposal to South 
Korean President Kim Yong-sam. 
  President Kim Yong-sam, upon hearing of Kim Il-song's wish 
to 
meet with him at any time, anywhere and at an early date without 
preconditions, told Carter that he will accept the offer 
"without any hesitation," presidential press secretary Chu 
Ton-sik told reporters. 
  Carter conveyed Kim Il-song's verbal message when briefing 
the south Korean president on the results of his Pyongyang trip. 
  Making a quick response to Kim Il-song's suggestion that 
"the 
earlier the summit came the better it would be," Kim Yong-sam 
said that "I myself think that the South-North Korean summit 
would be better the earlier it came," Chu quoted the South 
Korean president as saying. 
  Observers here believed that barring some unexpected 
developments, the inter-Korean summit is likely to be held in 
the near future, for the first time in the half-century of 
national division on the Korean peninsula. The venue of the 
summit can be either in Seoul, Pyongyang or at a third place. 
  Officials sources said that South Korea and the DPRK are 
expected to begin working-level contacts soon to discuss details 
of the planned summit meeting. 
  Carter's shuttling between Seoul and Pyongyang was a bid to 
break the deadlock over the DPRK's controversial nuclear program. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

