<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports ROK Preparations for Inter-Korean Summit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Reports ROK Preparations for Inter-Korean Summit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1906144594 Beijing XINHUA in English 1422 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1906144594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 19 (XINHUA) -- South Korea began full 
preparations today for the inter-Korean summit meeting between 
South Korean President Kim Yong-sam and President Kim Il-song of 
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK). 
  President Kim Yong-sam on Saturday [18 June] accepted the 
proposal made by President Kim Il-song to hold talks aimed at 
resolving the nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula. 
  South Korea's National Unification Board (NUB) has formed a 
working-level task force headed by Vice-Minister song Yong-tae 
and including other high-ranking officials. 
  The task force is making a variety of preparations for the 
summit, said an NUB official, who added that its members are now 
engaged in discussions of details, such as the date and venue of 
the summit. 
  Meanwhile, the South Korean Government has decided to hold a 
high-level strategy meeting on Monday to coordinate its position 
on the inter-Korean summit and discuss measures for dealing with 
the DPRK's nuclear issue. 
  South Korea and the DPRK are expected to hold working-level 
talks soon to discuss details relating to the summit, according 
to official sources here. 
  In a related development, former U.S. President Jimmy Carter 
left here today for home, following his six-day visit to 
Pyongyang and Seoul. 
  On Saturday, Carter conveyed DPRK President Kim Il-song's 
proposal for a summit to South Korean President Kim Yong-sam, 
who accepted immediately. 
  During his stay on the Korean peninsula, Carter exchanged 
views with South Korean and DPRK leaders on the nuclear issue in 
a bid to break the deadlock. 

</TEXT>

